❓ Q1 — Design a Secure Checkout System
You must cover:
	• Authentication
	• Authorization
	• API security
	• Payment flow
	• Order data
	• Mobile + web + backend
	• Fraud / bot detection
	• Logging & monitoring

✅ Answer (Structured)
1️⃣ Identity & Authentication
	• Use OAuth2/JWT for both web and mobile.
	• Short-lived access tokens + refresh tokens.
	• Enforce MFA for high-risk operations (e.g., payment change).
2️⃣ Authorization & Access Control
	• Validate user authorization for every API.
	• No client-side assumptions.
	• Use ABAC (Attribute-based) for fine-grained checks (userId == order.userId).
3️⃣ Data & Network Protection
	• TLS everywhere (mobile and web).
	• Sensitive fields encrypted both in transit and at rest (card tokens).
	• Use a secure payment gateway (PCI DSS compliance).
4️⃣ Threat & Abuse Mitigation
	• Idempotency keys for checkout to prevent replay/double spend.
	• Rate limiting per user/IP/device.
	• Strong bot detection (fingerprinting + challenge).
	• JWT stored securely (keychain/keystore on mobile).
5️⃣ Detection & Monitoring
	• Log all checkouts with correlation IDs.
	• Use SIEM to detect spikes, anomalies, shared device patterns.
	• Alerts for unusual refund/fraud patterns.

🔥 Follow-Up Trap #1:
 “How do you prevent someone from creating fake orders to drain inventory?”
🎯 Answer
	• Enforce CAPTCHA at suspicious threshold.
	• Use device fingerprinting.
	• Risk score based on velocity and patterns.
	• Quarantine high-risk orders for manual review.

🔥 Follow-Up Trap #2:
“What if JWT is stolen from mobile?”
🎯 Answer
	• Use short expiry + refresh token rotation.
	• Track device fingerprints and geolocation.
	• Revoke tokens for suspicious sessions.
	• Detect via behavioral analytics.

❓ Q2 — Secure API Architecture for Microservices

✅ Answer (Structured)
1️⃣ Identity & Authentication
	• API Gateway with JWT validation.
	• Internal mTLS between services.
	• API keys for third-party integrations.
2️⃣ Authorization & Access Control
	• Central policy engine (OPA/Policy as Code).
	• Partial trust at gateway → full check at service.
3️⃣ Data & Network
	• Zero trust between services.
	• Service mesh with RBAC at service level.
	• Limits on privileges per service.
4️⃣ Threat & Abuse
	• Rate limiting and quotas at gateway.
	• Request size limits, JSON schema validation.
	• Rejection of unexpected fields (mass assignment).
5️⃣ Monitoring
	• Centralized audit logging.
	• Tracing (context propagation).
	• Anomaly detection (e.g., BOLA attempts).

🔥 Follow-Up Trap:
“Should authorization be done only at the gateway?”
🎯 Answer:
No — gateway provides coarse authZ.
Critical object-level authorization must be enforced at the microservice that owns the data.

❓ Q3 — Secure Mobile + API Architecture (Preventing API Abuse)
Focus on trust boundaries.

✅ Answer (Structured)
1️⃣ Identity
	• OAuth2/JWT
	• Device binding (unique device ID/token)
2️⃣ Authorization
	• Mobile app never trusted for authZ.
	• Validate everything server-side.
3️⃣ Data & Network
	• TLS + certificate pinning.
4️⃣ Threat & Abuse
	• Bot detection
	• Behavioral anomalies
	• Abuse patterns (coupon, inventory scraping, wallet steal)
5️⃣ Monitoring
	• Correlate mobile device pedigree
	• Detect emulator/sandbox usage
	• Track failed retries and velocity spikes

🔥 Follow-Up:
“How do you handle rooted/jailbroken devices?”
🎯 Answer:
	• Detect at runtime
	• Apply risk score (restrict sensitive actions)
	• Not block entirely — balance UX
	• Log + alert suspicious sessions

❓ Q4 — Design Secure Cloud Architecture for Multi-Region E-commerce
	• Availability + resiliency
	• Failover
	• Data protection
	• Least privilege
	• Secure communication

✅ Answer
1️⃣ Identity
	• Federation (SAML/OIDC) for workforce
	• Short-lived roles for services
2️⃣ Authorization
	• Role separation by region
	• Cross-account roles with strict trust
3️⃣ Data & Network
	• VPC isolation
	• Private subnets + endpoints
	• Avoid public API access where possible
4️⃣ Threat & Abuse
	• Encryption
	• Backup with immutability
	• Guardrails (CSPM/SecOps automation)
5️⃣ Monitoring
	• Central SIEM
	• Central logging aggregators
	• Active tracing across services

🔥 Follow-Up:
“What if attacker hits a region failover?”
🎯 Answer:
Design with:
	• Health-checked routing
	• Automated rollbacks
	• Canary releases
	• Immutable infrastructure

❓ Q5 — Secure AI/ML Service Architecture

✅ Answer
1️⃣ Identity
	• Service authentication with mTLS + short-lived keys
2️⃣ Authorization
	• Role separation between training/admin and inference
3️⃣ Data & Network
	• Train data storage encrypted
	• Egress control
4️⃣ Threat & Abuse
	• Protect against:
		○ Data poisoning
		○ Model extraction
		○ Prompt injection
		○ Model inversion
5️⃣ Monitoring
	• Model behavior monitoring
	• Drift detection
	• Anomalous query patterns

🔥 Follow-Up:
“How do you prevent prompt injection in LLM APIs?”
🎯 Answer:
	• Context sanitization
	• Guardrails via prompt policies
	• Reject malicious patterns
	• Semantic anomaly detection

❓ Q6 — How do you ensure secure data processing pipelines?
This is web/cloud crossover.

✅ Answer
1️⃣ Identity
	• Least privilege
2️⃣ Authorization
	• Policy enforcement
3️⃣ Data
	• Encryption
	• Tokenization
4️⃣ Threat
	• Pipeline integrity
	• Version control
	• Hashing & checksums
5️⃣ Monitoring
	• Audit trails
	• Alerts for schema anomalies

❓ Q7 — Secure DevOps / CI/CD Architecture

✅ Answer
1️⃣ Identity
	• Minimal CI runner permissions
2️⃣ Authorization
	• Approval workflows
	• RBAC in pipelines
3️⃣ Data
	• Secrets in vaults
4️⃣ Threat
	• Scan IaC
	• SAST/DAST gates
5️⃣ Monitoring
	• Audit pipeline events
	• Alerts on risky changes

❓ Q8 — How to design defense-in-depth?

✅ Answer
Defense-in-depth means:
Layer 1 — Network (firewalls, VPC)
Layer 2 — Perimeter (API GW)
Layer 3 — Auth (JWT, MFA)
Layer 4 — AuthZ (RBAC/ABAC)
Layer 5 — App Security (validation, logic)
Layer 6 — Monitoring & IR
Say:
	“The goal is redundant protection so if one layer fails, another catches the risk.”

🔥 Follow-Up:
“Is WAF enough?”
🎯 Answer:
No — WAF helps but cannot replace secure coding, authorization, and fraud prevention.

❓ Q9 — How to handle security in microservices?

✅ Answer
	• API Gateway → coarse validation
	• Service mesh → identity + encryption
	• Central OPA policy → policy and access logic
	• Service → final authZ + business logic

❓ Q10 — How to evaluate security posture of architecture?

✅ Answer
Use metrics:
	• Vulnerability backlog
	• MTTR
	• % services scanned
	• % services threat-modeled
	• Breach attempts
	• Mean time to detect (MTTD)
You must tie to business.


🧠 FINAL RETENTION TRICK
For every architecture question, remember:
I.A.N.T.M
Identity
Authorization
Network/data
Threat reduction
Monitoring/response
If you can apply this pattern, you can handle ANY variant.
